article.description:
Temeka Johnson scored 24 points and grabbed nine rebounds to lead No. 5 and second-seeded LSU past No. 3 and first-seeded Tennessee, 78-62,
to win the Southeastern Conference tournament.
article.headline: LSU snaps Tennessee's 19-game winning streak
article.linkText: LSU upsets Lady Vols to win SEC Tournament
article.story:
NORTH LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- LSU coach Sue Gunter looked at
the Southeastern Conference tournament bracket and saw a special
opportunity.

	   To win the tourney title and the league's automatic bid to the
NCAA Tournament, the Lady Tigers (No. 5 ESPN/USA Today, No. 6 AP) would have to make up
for their three losses this season -- to Arkansas, Vanderbilt and
Tennessee.

	   LSU completed the task Sunday with a 78-62 victory over No. 3
Tennessee. Now Gunter hopes the Lady Tigers receive a No. 1 seed
from the NCAA selection committee when the announcements are made
March 16.

	   "One of our goals coming in that in order for us to win the
tournament we would have to defeat the three teams that had beaten
us,'' Gunter said. "I don't know what else we could possibly do to
earn (a No. 1 seed).''

	   Temeka Johnson did everything she could to carry LSU (27-3) past
Tennessee with 24 points and a game-high nine rebounds. The
5-foot-3 junior point guard energized the Lady Tigers' offense with
seven assists, and the Lady Volunteers (28-4) never got closer than
12 points in the second half.

	   "Temeka Johnson is a difference-maker for them,'' Tennessee
coach Pat Summitt said. "They pushed the ball in transition and
made plays. We didn't have an answer for her.''

	   Johnson earned tournament most valuable player honors after
scoring 51 points with 14 rebounds and 15 assists in LSU's three
tournament victories. She scored most of her points against
Tennessee, beating her defender to the basket for easy layups.

	   "Everybody likes to play us in a zone and I guess Tennessee
being stubborn likes to plays us in a man,'' Johnson said. "That
just gets me motivated.''

	   LSU won its first league tourney title since 1991, when it beat
Tennessee. The Lady Tigers snapped the Lady Volunteers' 19-game
winning streak, which was tied for the nation's fifth longest. The
winning streak included a 14-0 league record and a regular-season
SEC title.

	   Tennessee, which had not advanced to the tournament final since
winning its third straight in 2000, lost for the first time in an
SEC final since Vanderbilt beat it in 1995.

	   Senior Aiysha Smith added 18 points for LSU, while freshman
Seimone Augustus had 12 points and eight rebounds.

	   Kara Lawson, who put Tennessee in the tournament final with a
last-second shot against Mississippi State on Saturday, paced the
Lady Volunteers with 16 points, while Shanna Zolman had 15.

	   Absent for the second straight game for the Lady Volunteers was
an inside scoring presence. Leading scorer Gwen Jackson was held to
eight points, while starting center Ashley Robinson had 13 points
in the tournament.

	   "I'm very disappointed in the lack of scoring from our inside
game,'' Summitt said. "It's been glaring all weekend. I think we
have to establish a better scoring output from all of our inside
players. We need consistency.''

	   After Tennessee closed to 61-49 with 7:26 remaining, the Lady
Volunteers went just 3-of-12 the rest of the game.

	   Tennessee was 1-for-13 from 3-point range, not making one until
Zolman connected with less than a minute remaining.

	   For the third straight game, the Lady Volunteers started slow
and fell behind. Tennessee trailed Auburn and Mississippi State by
nine at halftime in its first two games of the tournament, but LSU
almost doubled that.

	   Tennessee missed its first five shots and had four turnovers
before Zolman came off the bench to score its first basket with
15:05 left in the first half.

	   Three turnovers fueled an 8-0 LSU run that gave the Lady Tigers
a 17-8 lead.

	   Zolman stopped the run with a long jumper, but then Roneeka
Hodges scored six straight points as LSU surged ahead 23-10.
Doneeka Hodges hit a 3-pointer with 2:10 remaining in the half to
give the Lady Tigers a 38-23 lead.

	   "We didn't play well at this tournament in any of the first
halves,'' Summitt said. "Why? I'm going to hold our starters
accountable for that. It's taking responsibility for coming out and
playing defense and scoring.''

	   Johnson, who had 15 points and seven rebounds in the first half,
scored a fast-break basket after Tennessee's ninth turnover of the
half, and a layup by Smith gave the Lady Tigers a 42-25 halftime
lead.
